\]

Yes, exactly. So, the equation becomes \((x + 1)^3 = 0\), which has a triple root at \(x = -1\). So, all roots are real (they are all equal to -1). Therefore, at \(a = 3\), the equation has all real roots.

But wait, is this the only point where the discriminant is zero? Because in the discriminant expression, we had \((a - 3)^3 (a + 1)\), so the discriminant is zero when \(a = 3\) or \(a = -1\). But since \(a\) is positive, only \(a = 3\) is relevant.

So, for \(a > 3\), the discriminant is positive, meaning three distinct real roots. For \(0 < a < 3\), the discriminant is negative, meaning one real root and two complex conjugate roots. Therefore, the minimal \(a\) for which all roots are real is indeed 3.

